          "body": "Into the middle of the Samaritan revival walks Luke’s most disturbing case study. Simon, a long-established sorcerer who has been *astonishing* (existemi) the Samaritans and being called “the Great Power of God” (8:9-10), now finds himself displaced by Philip’s greater signs. Luke says he *believed and was baptized* (8:13). Yet when he sees the Spirit given through apostolic hands, he offers money for the same authority — the sin that has carried his name ever since (“simony”). Peter’s rebuke is severe and clinical: *your heart is not right before God* (8:21); *you are in the gall of bitterness and in the bondage of iniquity* (8:23). The diagnosis exposes that Simon’s “faith” had been amazement at *power*, not submission to *Christ*. The chapter forces a sobering observation: profession, baptism, and association with apostles do not by themselves indicate regeneration. Peter’s prescription is the same one given to every awakened sinner — repent and pray (8:22). Whether Simon ever did is left ambiguous; his response (8:24) asks Peter to pray for him but stops short of repenting himself."
